# docs/DECISIONS.md

An append-only architecture decision log (ADR-001 through ADR-046) for the CTX project — a context-summarization/access-control system whose reference consumer is an external meal-planning CLI (`../meal-planning/`). This file records *why* — rejected alternatives and rationale — not current behavior; current behavior lives in `SPEC.md` and the code itself. `intent.md` files across the repo point here rather than restate it.

**Rule for editors:** never rewrite or delete an entry — supersede it with a new ADR that references the old one (`[[ADR-NNN]]`-style backlinks are used throughout). Status lines (`Status: accepted`, `Status: superseded by ADR-NNN`) track this. Several ADRs explicitly amend or supersede earlier ones without deleting them (e.g. ADR-011→ADR-022, ADR-024→ADR-025, ADR-028→ADR-029, ADR-032 corrects an overclaim in ADR-031, ADR-040 supersedes the cage transport of ADR-026/034, ADR-044/045 iterate on ADR-038's ignore-scope design).

Key architectural through-line an editor should know before touching `sandbox`/`ctx-cage`/`ctx-context`/`ctx-summarize`/`ctx-core`: the project pivoted twice. First (ADR-026→034) toward a strict enforcement cage (bwrap namespace + broker forcing all source access through `ctx-access`/`ctx-verify`), proven to work end-to-end (ADR-031, corrected in ADR-032, fully validated in ADR-033). Then (ADR-035 onward) it deliberately *dropped* enforcement-by-masking in favor of "lead-by-hooks": agents get native Read/Edit, a Claude Code `PostToolUse` hook injects the context chain automatically, and the cage was rebuilt (ADR-040) as a pure safety boundary (RW workspace bind, no broker, no source-masking) rather than an access-control mechanism. `ctx-access` was renamed/shrunk to `ctx-context` (ADR-036, read-only chain printer, no lifecycle/task-id).

Other load-bearing facts: nutrition math is fixed-point/integer by design (ADR-003), never floats. Freshness of summaries is tracked via a content-hash tree (`CACT`, ADR-038) plus `.ctxignore` scoping (seeded once from `.gitignore`, then sole authority — ADR-045), not git state or timestamps. Regeneration of summaries happens in exactly one place — post-session via `ctx-run`'s `ctx-scan --update` — never mid-session (ADR-043). The deny/scope gate for direct-target access and the walker now share one `.ctxignore`-based matcher (ADR-044); the secret/binary denylist itself lives only in `ctx-core` (ADR-023) and must never be duplicated. Egress for the caged agent is a host-side passthrough proxy over a UNIX socket, auth via the operator's Claude subscription credential, never an API key baked into the agent (ADR-041, reaffirming ADR-029). The workspace is bound at its real host path, not a fixed alias like `/work` (ADR-046) — relevant if compiled test binaries bake in `CARGO_MANIFEST_DIR`.

If editing `ctx-verify`, `ctx-scan`, `ctx-cage`, or the sandbox scripts, check here first for why a prior design was rejected before reintroducing it — several rejected alternatives (git-diff-based freshness, `/dev/null` secret masks, fixed cage aliases, embedded prompts, an API-key spend path) are one-line traps that were already tried and reverted.